Just to get this out of unanswered questions queue...

The times you&#39;re observing are identical because in the following loop the compiler optimizes the test away, since the value `areEqual` is never used:

```C++
  for (auto _ : state) {
    bool areEqual = ip1 == ip2;
  }
```

In Google Benchmark you can prevent that from happening with [`benchmark::DoNotOptimize()`][1]:

```C++
  for (auto _ : state) {
    bool areEqual = ip1 == ip2;
    benchmark::DoNotOptimize(areEqual);
  }
```

Now the difference can be [seen][2]:

[![benchmark int vs string comparison][3]][3]

---

(Another clue that the test is optimized away on [quick-bench.com][4] is the empty &quot;generated assembly&quot; output)


